<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-641-680  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 641 680.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  June 28 1990 n1220 p30(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How to dictate your own terms. (computerizing a business)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miller, Nigel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>When selecting hardware and software for a business be sure thatany pre-contract correspondence, particularly letters of intent,clearly state that the terms are subject to the signing of aformal contract.andP;  Be sure to carefully examine the terms of thecontract and negotiate the prices, payment and delivery termsbefore signing anything.andP;  The contract should fully identify eachpiece of equipment and software and all price, payment, delivery,training, manuals, and installation fees should be clearly stated.andO;The contract should also provide for post-installation testingon-site; mere acceptance of delivery of the equipment does notsatisfy the purchaser's needs.andP;  If it is necessary to reveal allaspects of your business in order to design a computer system,make sure to include a detailed confidentiality clause in thecontract.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer SystemsSmall BusinessEquipment AcquisitionContractsManagement of EDPAutomationInstalling a ComputerGuidelines.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>